Prospera OS
Audience Classifier Specification v1.0

File: system/audience/audience-classifier-v1.0.md
Status: Stable
Owner: Prospera Architecture Group
Category: System Specification

──────────────────────────────────────────────

1. Purpose

The Audience Classifier is the deterministic component of the Audience System responsible for identifying and assigning the base audience type used throughout Prospera OS.

It ensures that all downstream systems (Intent, Modeling, Safety, Routing, Generation, Execution) operate on a consistent, validated, and non-probabilistic audience classification.

──────────────────────────────────────────────

2. Scope

This specification defines:
• classification categories
• deterministic classification rules
• upstream/downstream dependencies
• safety constraints
• governance alignment
• SSOT write-back requirements
• prohibited operations

The Audience Classifier produces the canonical audience-type used across the OS.

──────────────────────────────────────────────

3. Classification Outputs

The classifier generates the following fields:

3.1 audience-type

Singular, non-ambiguous identifier describing the target audience.
Examples:
• general
• professional
• expert
• beginner
• corporate
• executive
• technical

3.2 demographic-class

Optional structural metadata (non-sensitive).
Examples:
• working-adult
• senior-professional
• student
• practitioner

3.3 expertise-level

Defines information complexity tier.
Values:
• low
• medium
• high
• domain-expert

3.4 interaction-profile

Behavioral mode describing expected interaction pattern.
Examples:
• concise
• narrative
• step-based
• analytical
• executive-summary

All outputs must be deterministic and validated by Safety + Governance layers.

──────────────────────────────────────────────

4. Deterministic Classification Rules
4.1 Single-Value Rule

Classifier must always output one and only one audience-type.

If classification ambiguity occurs → Drift event → Recovery → Re-classify.

4.2 Deterministic Rule

Classifier must not use probabilistic inference.
If upstream provides ambiguous modeling signals, classifier must fallback to SSOT history.

4.3 Traceability Rule

Every classification must contain:
• source-signals
• rule-path
• confidence-threshold validation
• safety-check result
• timestamp

4.4 Non-Override Rule

No subsystem may override classifier output unless:
• Safety → detects risk
• Governance → mandates override
• SSOT → detects conflict

4.5 Alignment Rule

Classifier must align with:
• Identity System
• Intent System
• User Modeling System

Mismatch triggers a drift event.

──────────────────────────────────────────────

5. Inputs

The Audience Classifier consumes deterministic upstream signals.

5.1 Required Inputs

• identity-role
• intent-type
• modeling-preferences
• task-context
• execution-environment

5.2 Optional Inputs

• historical SSOT audience logs
• validated long-term behavioral patterns

5.3 Forbidden Inputs

Classifier may not use:
• personal data
• probabilistic user modeling
• third-party platform classifications
• inferred demographic attributes

──────────────────────────────────────────────

6. Downstream Responsibilities

Classifier outputs feed:

6.1 Audience Matrix

→ maps audience-type to routing and generation constraints.

6.2 Audience State Machine

→ defines initial state: Classified.

6.3 Routing System

→ defines content format, tone, and complexity.

6.4 Generation System

→ determines structural density, terminology boundaries, and explanation depth.

6.5 Safety System

→ enforces audience-appropriate constraints.

──────────────────────────────────────────────

7. Safety Requirements

The classifier must block downstream execution if:

• audience-type is undefined
• classifier rules contradict intent
• identity intent mismatch
• safety-level for target audience is violated
• drift is detected mid-pipeline

If safety violation → hard block + escalate.

──────────────────────────────────────────────

8. SSOT Requirements

Classifier must write to SSOT:

• audience-type
• reasoning-path
• validation-hash
• drift-events
• safety-alignment-status

SSOT must remain immutable after write-back.

──────────────────────────────────────────────

9. Forbidden Operations

The Audience Classifier may never:

• generate multivalued audience types
• hallucinate demographic attributes
• rewrite user identity
• override intent or modeling
• modify routing rules
• bypass Governance
• read Kernel-level data
• operate probabilistically
• store sensitive attributes

Violation → enforcement + Governance escalation.

──────────────────────────────────────────────

10. Versioning

v1.0 Initial Audience Classifier Specification
v1.1 Multi-Domain Audience Schema
v2.x Adaptive Audience Classification Model

